		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_CIV5_RESOURCE_TIN_TEXT">
			<Text>Tin is a metal obtained chiefly from the mineral, cassiterite. Tin extraction and use can be dated to the beginnings of the Bronze Age around 3000 BC, where it was much sought after. When combined with copper it creates a stronger and much more useful alloy, bronze.  Today, tin is a major ingredient used in solder. It is also used as plating to help other metals resist corrosion, and because of its low toxicity, this includes the plating of cans for food packaging.</Text>
